        "\n",
        "### 1.1 Dataset Overview\n",
        "The Flight Delay Dataset 2024 is a comprehensive record of domestic flight operations throughout the year 2024. It was sourced from the Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS) and made publicly available on Kaggle. The dataset tracks the on-time performance of flights operated by all major US airlines, including departure delays, arrival delays, cancellations, and the specific causes of each delay (carrier-related, weather-related, National Aviation System, security, and late aircraft).\n",
        "\n",
        "The dataset contains 35 columns covering flight identifiers, airline codes, origin and destination airports, scheduled and actual departure and arrival times, delay durations in minutes, and binary flags for cancellations and diversions. With over 7.2 million rows and a file size of 1.22 GB, this dataset substantially exceeds the 700 MB minimum requirement and presents a genuine challenge to standard data processing tools.\n",
        "\n",
        "This dataset was selected because it is large enough to stress-test all five handling strategies, diverse enough in its column types to demonstrate meaningful data type optimisation, and rich enough analytically to support aggregation, grouping, and exploratory operations across all three libraries.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 2.0 Library Choices\n",
        "| Role | Library | Version |\n",
        "|---|---|---|\n",
        "| **Library 1 (Compulsory Baseline)** | Pandas | 2.2.2 |\n",
        "| **Library 2 (Scalable)** | Dask | 2026.3.0 |\n",
        "| **Library 3 (Scalable)** | Polars | 1.35.2 |\n",
        "\n",
        "### 2.1 Justification of choosing Dask Library\n",
        "Dask was chosen as our second library because it mirrors the Pandas API almost exactly, making it the most direct comparison point for understanding what changes when you move from single-threaded to parallel processing. Dask splits large datasets into partitions and processes them in parallel across available CPU cores. It supports lazy evaluation, meaning operations are not executed until `.compute()` is called, allowing Dask to optimise the execution plan beforehand. Dask is particularly well-suited for CSV files and DataFrame operations at scale, which aligns directly with our dataset format.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 2.1 Justification of choosing Polars Library\n",
        "Polars was chosen as our third library because it represents the state of the art in single-machine large-data processing. Written in Rust with an Apache Arrow columnar memory backend, Polars delivers exceptional speed through compiled execution (eliminating Python's interpreter overhead), lazy query planning (where `.collect()` triggers an optimised execution plan), and automatic projection and predicate pushdown. Polars is increasingly adopted in production data engineering environments, and comparing it directly against both Pandas and Dask allows us to understand the full performance spectrum from baseline to cutting-edge.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3. Data Loading and Inspection\n",
        "### 3.1 Environment Setup\n",
        "Before loading the dataset, the environment was configured as follows:\n",
        "```python\n",
