        "\n",
        "**Observation:** The default Pandas load assigns `object` type to all text columns and `float64` to all numeric columns regardless of their actual value ranges. This is wasteful — for example, `Cancelled` only ever holds 0 or 1, yet Pandas allocates 8 bytes per row for it. These inefficiencies are addressed in Strategy 3.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 4. Big Data Handling Strategies\n",
        "### 4.1 Load Less Data\n",
        "\n",
        "Load Less Data means specifying which columns to load from the CSV file, rather than reading all 35 columns by default. Only the 10 columns required for analysis are loaded using the `usecols` parameter.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "When a 35-column dataset is loaded in full but only 10 columns are needed, 25 columns are loaded into memory and immediately ignored. This is wasted RAM — memory that could otherwise be used for processing. By specifying columns upfront, Pandas reads and discards unused columns during parsing, reducing peak memory consumption before any processing begins.\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "SELECTED_COLS = [\n",
        "    'FlightDate', 'Airline', 'Origin', 'Dest',\n",
        "    'DepDelay', 'ArrDelay', 'Cancelled',\n",
        "    'Distance', 'CarrierDelay', 'WeatherDelay'\n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "tracemalloc.start()\n",
        "start = time.time()\n",
        "\n",
        "df_less = pd.read_csv(FILE_PATH, usecols=SELECTED_COLS)\n",
        "\n",
        "end = time.time()\n",
        "current, peak = tracemalloc.get_traced_memory()\n",
        "tracemalloc.stop()\n",
        "\n",
        "s1_time = end - start\n",
        "s1_memory = peak / (1024 ** 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Load Time    : {s1_time:.2f} seconds\")\n",
        "print(f\"Peak Memory  : {s1_memory:.2f} MB\")\n",
        "print(f\"Memory Saved : {baseline_memory - s1_memory:.2f} MB\")\n",
        "print(f\"Reduction    : {((baseline_memory - s1_memory)/baseline_memory*100):.1f}%\")\n",
        "```\n",
        "**Output:**\n",
        "```\n",
        "Load Time    : 29.90 seconds\n",
        "Peak Memory  : 1577.94 MB\n",
        "Memory Saved : 4607.14 MB\n",
        "Reduction    : 74.5%\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Discussion\n",
        "\n",
        "Restricting data ingestion to the 10 target columns dropped the peak memory requirement from 6185.07 MB to 1577.94 MB, achieving a 74.5% reduction in memory usage. This demonstrates that identifying required attributes before loading data is a highly effective way to eliminate processing waste without altering the data structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### 4.2 Chunking\n",
        "\n",
        "Chunking reads the CSV file in fixed-size portions (chunks) rather than all at once. Each chunk is processed individually, and only one chunk exists in memory at any given time.\n",
        "\n",
        "Without chunking, loading a 1.22 GB file allocates a large continuous block of RAM. In a Google Colab free-tier environment with approximately 12 GB of RAM, this is feasible but leaves limited headroom for processing. Chunking caps the memory used at any moment to the size of one chunk, making it possible in principle to process a file larger than available RAM. It is essential for environments with strict memory constraints.\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "CHUNK_SIZE = 500_000\n",
        "\n",
        "tracemalloc.start()\n",
        "start = time.time()\n",
        "\n",
        "chunk_results = []\n",
        "\n",
        "for chunk in pd.read_csv(FILE_PATH, usecols=SELECTED_COLS, chunksize=CHUNK_SIZE):\n",
        "    grp = chunk.groupby('Airline')['DepDelay'].agg(['sum', 'count'])\n",
        "    chunk_results.append(grp)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Combine all partial results\n",
        "combined = pd.concat(chunk_results).groupby(level=0).sum()\n",
        "combined['avg_dep_delay'] = combined['sum'] / combined['count']\n",
        "\n",
        "end = time.time()\n",
        "current, peak = tracemalloc.get_traced_memory()\n",
        "tracemalloc.stop()\n",
        "\n",
        "s2_time = end - start\n",
        "s2_memory = peak / (1024 ** 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Chunk Size   : {CHUNK_SIZE:,} rows\")\n",
        "print(f\"Load Time    : {s2_time:.2f} seconds\")\n",
        "print(f\"Peak Memory  : {s2_memory:.2f} MB\")\n",
        "print(\"\\nAverage Departure Delay by Airline:\")\n",
        "print(combined['avg_dep_delay'].sort_values(ascending=False).head(10))\n",
        "```\n",
        "**Output:**\n",
        "```\n",
        "Chunk Size   : 500,000 rows\n",
        "Load Time    : 30.29 seconds\n",
        "Peak Memory  : 151.39 MB\n",
        "\n",
        "Average Departure Delay by Airline:\n",
        "op_unique_carrier\n",
        "AA    20.698095\n",
        "F9    19.002299\n",
        "B6    17.458447\n",
        "NK    14.957090\n",
        "G4    14.047917\n",
        "OH    13.936732\n",
        "UA    11.959024\n",
        "WN    11.748603\n",
        "OO    11.279937\n",
        "DL    10.223549\n",
        "Name: avg_dep_delay, dtype: float64\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Discussion\n",
        "\n",
        "Chunking isolated the execution environment, lowering peak memory usage to just 151.39 MB—a 97.5% memory reduction compared to the baseline load. To ensure mathematical accuracy, the loop tracks intermediate sub-counts and sums. Calculating simple averages within individual chunks can cause statistical errors due to varying chunk sizes; combining raw sub-components across segments preserves total accuracy.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### 4.3 Data Type Optimisation\n",
        "\n",
        "Data type optimisation identifies columns whose default assigned types use more memory than necessary and converts them to smaller, more appropriate types. This is applied after loading the data and before any major processing.\n",
        "\n",
        "Pandas assigns `float64` (8 bytes per value) to all numeric columns and `object` (variable, often 50+ bytes per string) to all text columns by default. For a 7-million-row dataset, this is extremely wasteful. Converting float columns to `float32` (4 bytes) halves their memory cost. Converting string columns with few unique values (such as Airline, with only ~20 unique names across 7 million rows) to `category` type stores each string once and uses a compact integer code for every row, dramatically reducing memory.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Implementation\n",
        "```python\n",
        "df_opt = pd.read_csv(FILE_PATH, usecols=SELECTED_COLS)\n",
        "before_memory = df_opt.memory_usage(deep=True).sum() / (1024 ** 2)\n",
        "print(f\"Memory BEFORE: {before_memory:.2f} MB\")\n",
        "print(\"\\nData types BEFORE:\")\n",
        "print(df_opt.dtypes)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Downcast float columns from float64 to float32\n",
        "float_cols = ['DepDelay', 'ArrDelay', 'CarrierDelay', 'WeatherDelay', 'Distance']\n",
        "for col in float_cols:\n",
        "    df_opt[col] = pd.to_numeric(df_opt[col], downcast='float')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Convert high-cardinality string columns to category\n",
        "cat_cols = ['Airline', 'Origin', 'Dest']\n",
        "for col in cat_cols:\n",
        "    df_opt[col] = df_opt[col].astype('category')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Downcast binary flag from float64 to int8\n",
        "df_opt['Cancelled'] = df_opt['Cancelled'].astype('int8')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Convert date string to datetime\n",
        "df_opt['FlightDate'] = pd.to_datetime(df_opt['FlightDate'])\n",
        "\n",
        "after_memory = df_opt.memory_usage(deep=True).sum() / (1024 ** 2)\n",
        "print(f\"\\nMemory AFTER : {after_memory:.2f} MB\")\n",
        "print(f\"Reduction    : {((before_memory - after_memory)/before_memory*100):.1f}%\")\n",
        "print(\"\\nData types AFTER:\")\n",
        "print(df_opt.dtypes)\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "**Output:**\n",
        "```\n",
        "Memory BEFORE optimisation: 1768.80 MB\n",
        "\n",
        "Data types BEFORE:\n",
        "fl_date               object\n",
        "op_unique_carrier     object\n",
        "origin                object\n",
        "dest                  object\n",
        "dep_delay            float64\n",
        "arr_delay            float64\n",
        "cancelled              int64\n",
        "distance             float64\n",
        "carrier_delay          int64\n",
        "weather_delay          int64\n",
        "dtype: object\n",
        "\n",
        "Memory AFTER optimisation: 229.59 MB\n",
        "Memory Saved: 1539.21 MB\n",
        "Reduction   : 87.0%\n",
        "\n",
        "Data types AFTER:\n",
        "fl_date              datetime64[ns]\n",
        "op_unique_carrier          category\n",
        "origin                     category\n",
        "dest                       category\n",
        "dep_delay                   float32\n",
        "arr_delay                   float32\n",
        "cancelled                      int8\n",
        "distance                    float32\n",
        "carrier_delay               float32\n",
        "weather_delay               float32\n",
        "dtype: object\n",
        "```\n",
        "#### Memory Reduction Breakdown\n",
        "\n",
        "| Column(s) | Before | After | Saving per Value |\n",
        "|---|---|---|---|\n",
        "| DepDelay, ArrDelay, CarrierDelay, WeatherDelay, Distance | float64 (8 bytes) | float32 (4 bytes) | 50% |\n",
        "| Airline, Origin, Dest | object (~50 bytes avg) | category (~1–2 bytes) | ~97% |\n",
        "| Cancelled | float64 (8 bytes) | int8 (1 byte) | 87.5% |\n",
        "| FlightDate | object (~50 bytes) | datetime64 (8 bytes) | ~84% |\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Discussion\n",
        "\n",
        "Type downcasting compressed the dataset size from 1768.80 MB to 229.59 MB, saving 87.0% of system memory. The largest savings came from converting categorical flight properties (`op_unique_carrier`, `origin`, `dest`) from raw object strings to categorical values. Instead of repeatedly storing the same string values across 7 million rows, this strategy indexes unique values once and uses single-byte integer pointers for each row, optimizing performance while retaining full data precision.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### 4.4 Sampling\n",
        "\n",
        "Sampling selects a random representative subset of the full dataset for analysis. Rather than working with all 7.2 million rows, a sample of 200,000 rows is drawn and used for rapid exploratory analysis and code development.\n",
        "\n",
        "Developing and testing a data pipeline on 7.2 million rows is slow and resource-intensive. Any bug that surfaces after a 3-minute processing run wastes 3 minutes per iteration. A 200,000-row sample processes in seconds, enabling rapid iteration, debugging, and exploration. Once the analysis logic is validated on the sample, it can be applied to the full dataset with confidence. Sampling is standard practice in professional data science workflows.\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "tracemalloc.start()\n",
        "start = time.time()\n",
        "\n",
        "df_sample = pd.read_csv(FILE_PATH, usecols=SELECTED_COLS).sample(\n",
        "    n=200_000, random_state=42\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "end = time.time()\n",
        "current, peak = tracemalloc.get_traced_memory()\n",
        "tracemalloc.stop()\n",
        "\n",
        "s4_time = end - start\n",
        "s4_memory = peak / (1024 ** 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Sample Size      : {len(df_sample):,} rows\")\n",
        "print(f\"Sampling %       : {len(df_sample)/len(df_full)*100:.1f}% of full dataset\")\n",
        "print(f\"Time             : {s4_time:.2f} seconds\")\n",
        "print(f\"Peak Memory      : {s4_memory:.2f} MB\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Quick EDA on sample\n",
        "print(\"\\n=== Departure Delay Statistics (Sample) ===\")\n",
        "print(df_sample['DepDelay'].describe())\n",
        "\n",
