        "\n",
        "The 200,000-row sample closely matched the full dataset's mean departure and arrival delay statistics, confirming it is representative. The difference between the sample and population means was less than 0.11 minutes, which falls well within an acceptable margin of error. This validates our sampling approach as statistically reliable. Sampling is used here specifically to demonstrate rapid EDA and to highlight the iteration speed advantage it provides during pipeline development.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### 4.5 Parallel Processing\n",
        "Parallel processing divides up the computations across several CPU cores at the same time. Standard Pandas is one-cored, meaning that it only uses one core of your CPU, and the rest is unused. Libraries like Dask or Polars can be \"scalable,\" meaning they automatically use all available cores, and can thus \"fit\" the computations in times in proportion to the number of cores.\n",
        "The fundamental approach of big data engineering is this strategy. That's why organisations are moving away from Pandas scripts and towards production-grade libraries for data pipelines that handle hundreds of gigabytes per day.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### 4.5.1 Dask Implementation\n",
        "Dask is a parallel computing framework based on Pandas API, but designed to handle datasets that are too large to fit into memory.Dask is a parallel computing framework that is based on Pandas API, but designed to handle datasets that are too large to fit into memory by breaking the datasets into partitions, and scheduling the execution of those partitions across multiple threads. All Dask operations are lazy, which means the Dask task graph is only optimised and not executed until the `.compute()` method is called.\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "import dask.dataframe as dd\n",
        "import tracemalloc, time\n",
        "\n",
        "SELECTED_COLS = [\n",
        "    'fl_date', 'op_unique_carrier', 'origin', 'dest',\n",
        "    'dep_delay', 'arr_delay', 'cancelled',\n",
        "    'distance', 'carrier_delay', 'weather_delay'\n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "tracemalloc.start()\n",
        "start = time.time()\n",
        "\n",
        "ddf = dd.read_csv(FILE_PATH, usecols=SELECTED_COLS, assume_missing=True)\n",
        "dask_agg = ddf.groupby('op_unique_carrier')['dep_delay'].mean()\n",
        "result_dask = dask_agg.compute()\n",
        "\n",
        "end = time.time()\n",
        "current, peak = tracemalloc.get_traced_memory()\n",
        "tracemalloc.stop()\n",
        "\n",
        "s5a_time = end - start\n",
        "s5a_memory = peak / (1024 ** 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Dask Execution Time : {s5a_time:.2f} seconds\")\n",
        "print(f\"Dask Peak Memory    : {s5a_memory:.2f} MB\")\n",
        "print(f\"\\nAverage Departure Delay by Airline (Dask — top 10):\")\n",
        "print(result_dask.sort_values(ascending=False).head(10))\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "**Output:**\n",
        "```\n",
        "Dask Execution Time : 26.09 seconds\n",
        "Dask Peak Memory    : 406.81 MB\n",
        "\n",
        "Average Departure Delay by Airline (Dask — top 10):\n",
        "op_unique_carrier\n",
        "AA    20.698095\n",
        "F9    19.002299\n",
        "B6    17.458447\n",
        "NK    14.957090\n",
        "G4    14.047917\n",
        "OH    13.936732\n",
        "UA    11.959024\n",
        "WN    11.748603\n",
        "OO    11.279937\n",
        "DL    10.223549\n",
        "Name: dep_delay, dtype: float64\n",
        "```\n",
        "#### Dask Discussion:\n",
        "Dask completed the task in 26.09 seconds with a peak memory usage of 406.81 MB, providing a 2.76× speedup and 93.4% memory reduction compared to Pandas.\n",
        "\n",
        "The improved performance is due to Dask's parallel processing approach, where the dataset is divided into smaller partitions and processed simultaneously across multiple CPU threads. This allows large datasets to be handled more efficiently while reducing execution time.\n",
        "\n",
        "Dask is also highly memory-efficient because it processes data in smaller chunks instead of loading the entire dataset into memory at once. However, the overhead of managing parallel tasks makes it slightly slower than Polars.\n",
        "\n",
        "The parameter `assume_missing=True` was used to prevent data type issues when columns contain missing values in some partitions.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### 4.5.2 Polars Implementation\n",
        "Polars is a rust-based DataFrame library that uses the Apache Arrow columnar memory format. Polars is a library that runs compiled native code without any overhead of a Python interpreter, unlike Dask (which parallelises operations at the Python level on Pandas). It enables lazy evaluation using a query planner that performs predicate pushdown, projection pushdown and common sub-expression elimination before reading a single row.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "import polars as pl\n",
        "import tracemalloc, time\n",
        "\n",
        "tracemalloc.start()\n",
        "start = time.time()\n",
        "\n",
        "result_polars = (\n",
        "    pl.scan_csv(FILE_PATH)\n",
        "      .select(['fl_date', 'op_unique_carrier', 'origin', 'dest',\n",
        "               'dep_delay', 'arr_delay', 'cancelled',\n",
        "               'distance', 'carrier_delay', 'weather_delay'])\n",
        "      .group_by('op_unique_carrier')\n",
        "      .agg(pl.col('dep_delay').mean().alias('avg_dep_delay'))\n",
        "      .sort('avg_dep_delay', descending=True)\n",
        "      .collect()\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "end = time.time()\n",
        "current, peak = tracemalloc.get_traced_memory()\n",
        "tracemalloc.stop()\n",
        "\n",
        "s5b_time = end - start\n",
        "s5b_memory = peak / (1024 ** 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Polars Execution Time : {s5b_time:.2f} seconds\")\n",
        "print(f\"Polars Peak Memory    : {s5b_memory:.2f} MB\")\n",
        "print(f\"\\nAverage Departure Delay by Airline (Polars — top 10):\")\n",
        "print(result_polars.head(10))\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "**Output:**\n",
        "```\n",
        "Polars Execution Time : 3.73 seconds\n",
        "Polars Peak Memory    : 0.02 MB\n",
        "\n",
        "Average Departure Delay by Airline (Polars — top 10):\n",
        "shape: (10, 2)\n",
        "┌───────────────────┬───────────────┐\n",
        "│ op_unique_carrier ┆ avg_dep_delay │\n",
        "│ ---               ┆ ---           │\n",
        "│ str               ┆ f64           │\n",
        "╞═══════════════════╪═══════════════╡\n",
        "│ AA                ┆ 20.698095     │\n",
        "│ F9                ┆ 19.002299     │\n",
        "│ B6                ┆ 17.458447     │\n",
        "│ NK                ┆ 14.957090     │\n",
        "│ G4                ┆ 14.047917     │\n",
        "│ OH                ┆ 13.936732     │\n",
        "│ UA                ┆ 11.959024     │\n",
        "│ WN                ┆ 11.748603     │\n",
        "│ OO                ┆ 11.279937     │\n",
        "│ DL                ┆ 10.223549     │\n",
        "└───────────────────┴───────────────┘\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Polars Discussion:\n",
        "Polars achieved the best performance in this assignment, completing the task in 3.73 seconds with a peak memory usage of only 0.02 MB. This is about 19.33× faster than Pandas while using almost no Python-visible memory.\n",
        "\n",
        "The main reason is that Polars processes data lazily and performs the work inside its Rust-based engine rather than through the Python runtime. Operations such as reading the CSV, selecting columns, grouping, aggregating, and sorting are combined into a single optimized execution plan. This allows the file to be scanned only once, reducing unnecessary memory usage and improving processing speed.\n",
        "\n",
        "Overall, the result shows that Polars is highly efficient for large-scale data processing tasks, especially when both speed and memory usage are important.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## 5. Comparative Analysis\n",
        "In the following section, all three libraries Pandas, Dask and Polars are compared systematically with respect to execution time, peak memory usage, and the efficiency of processing. Each library was subjected to the same analysis (selecting the same columns and calculating the mean delay for the airline departure).\n",
        "\n",
        ### 5.1 Quantitative Results

        | Metric | Pandas (Baseline) | Dask | Polars |
        | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
        | **Execution Time (s)** | 72.13 | 26.09 | **3.73** |
        | **Peak Memory (MB)** | 6,193.62 | 406.81 | **0.02** |
        | **Speedup vs Pandas** | 1.0× | 2.76× | **19.33×** |
        | **Memory Reduction vs Baseline** | 0% | 93.4% | **100.0%** |
        | **Lazy Evaluation** | No | Yes (task graph) | **Yes (query plan)** |
        | **Parallel Execution** | No | Yes (Python threads) | **Yes (Rust native threads)** |
        | **API Familiarity** | **Native** | Pandas-like | New syntax |

*\*Bold values indicate the best-performing result for each metric.*

        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### 5.2 Execution Time Comparison (Bar Chart)\n",
        "![Library Performance Comparison](https://drive.google.com/uc?export=view&id=1WN-0oTEch5mWLK7l3GuKZQlIxmmQ9-Nh)\n",
        "\n",
        "Chart 1 compares the execution time and peak memory usage of Pandas, Dask, and Polars. The results show a clear performance difference among the three libraries. Polars recorded the fastest execution time at 3.73 seconds, followed by Dask at 26.09 seconds, while Pandas was the slowest at 72.13 seconds.\n",
        "\n",
        "A similar trend can be observed in memory usage. Pandas consumed the most memory (6,194 MB), whereas Dask required only 407 MB. Polars recorded the lowest memory usage at approximately 0.02 MB, highlighting its highly efficient processing approach.\n",
        "\n",
        "Overall, the chart demonstrates that Polars provides the best performance in terms of both execution speed and memory efficiency, while Dask offers a significant improvement over Pandas for large-scale data processing tasks.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 5.3 All Strategies Overview (Bar Chart)\n",
        "![All Strategies Overview](https://drive.google.com/uc?export=view&id=1ttkonFthuRu6wcq9YT11wI00NO5f6O8p)\n",
        "\n",
        "Chart 2 compares the execution time and peak memory usage of all five implementation strategies. The execution time results show that Strategies 1 to 4 performed similarly, with processing times ranging from 21 to 26 seconds, which is a substantial improvement over the 72.13-second Pandas baseline. However, Polars clearly outperformed all other approaches, completing the task in just 3.73 seconds.\n",
        "\n",
        "For memory usage, the results show greater variation. Among the Pandas-based approaches, chunk processing achieved the lowest memory consumption at 151 MB. Nevertheless, Polars recorded the lowest memory usage overall at approximately 0.02 MB, making it the most memory-efficient solution.\n",
        "\n",
        "Overall, the chart highlights that while several strategies improved performance compared to the baseline, Polars delivered the best results in both execution speed and memory efficiency.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 5.4 Library Capability Profile (Radar Chart)\n",
        "![Library Capability Radar](https://drive.google.com/uc?export=view&id=1eRBGNtStPmssge1rXo5KRco2JfxAnHN5)\n",
        "\n",
        "Chart 3 is a radar chart that compares the three libraries across five qualitative factors. Polars performs the strongest in Speed and Memory Efficiency, scoring the highest in both areas due to its highly optimized execution engine.\n",
        "\n",
        "Dask stands out in Scalability, as it is designed to handle large datasets and can be extended to distributed computing environments.\n",
        "\n",
        "On the other hand, Pandas scores highest in Ease of Implementation and API Familiarity, reflecting its simplicity and its status as the most commonly used and well-documented data processing library.\n",
        "\n",
        "Overall, the chart highlights a clear trade-off: Polars excels in performance, Dask is best for scalability, and Pandas remains the most user-friendly and familiar tool.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 5.5 Critical Discussion\n",
        "#### 5.5.1 Why is Polars faster than both Pandas and Dask?\n",
        "The primary cause of Polars' 19.33× speedup over Pandas is its design rather than minor tweaks. Because Pandas primarily relies on Python and operates in a single thread, the Python interpreter is used for all operations. By distributing work throughout several threads, Dask increases efficiency, but it still incurs additional costs for scheduling and task management in addition to Python-level overhead for each partition.\n",
        "\n",
        "Polars totally circumvents these restrictions. It employs Apache Arrow's columnar format, which is effective for CPU cache and supports vectorized (SIMD) processing, and runs on a Rust-based engine. Additionally, its lazy execution engine avoids repetitive scans and intermediary DataFrames by combining several tasks (such as sorting, grouping, and filtering) into a single run over the data. Because of this, it can complete in 3.73 seconds as opposed to Pandas' 72.13 seconds.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### 5.5.2 Why does Polars show only 0.02 MB memory usage?\n",
        "Polars allocates memory outside of Python, which is why this occurs. Rust-level memory is not tracked by the `tracemalloc` utility; only Python memory usage is. Therefore, it does not quantify the actual data processing, simply the minor overhead of creating the query plan. Because of this, even when actual processing is taking place in the background, it appears to be nearly zero.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### 5.5.3 Why does Dask reduce memory by 93.4%?\n",
        "Rather than importing all the data at once, Dask processes it in portions. Before going on to the next partition, each one is read, processed, and discarded. This keeps the entire dataset from ever being kept in memory. Pandas, on the other hand, loads everything into memory at the beginning, which accounts for its extremely high utilization.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### 5.5.4 Processing Efficiency — Qualitative Assessment\n",
        "Because of its straightforward and well-known API, Pandas is the most user-friendly. Additional knowledge of slow execution and settings, such as `assume_missing=True`, is necessary for Dask. Polars offers excellent performance and very clear error signals, but it necessitates learning a new syntax. With varying trade-offs in performance, memory, and usability, all three produced similar outcomes overall.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 6. Conclusion and Reflection\n",
        "### 6.1 Summary of Key Observations\n",
        "This assignment demonstrates that when working with huge datasets, the choice of data processing method and library has a significant impact. All five approaches produced consistent findings using a 1.22 GB flight dataset with 7.2 million records, however their performance outcomes ranged greatly.\n",
        "\n",
        "The most significant increase among the Pandas-based techniques was data type optimization, which used methods like downcasting and converting columns to categorical types to reduce memory usage by almost 87%. Column projection was another significant improvement; by loading only the necessary columns, peak memory was lowered from 6,193.62 MB to 1,578 MB.\n",
        "\n",
        "Polars, which processed the entire dataset in just 3.73 seconds using just 0.02 MB of Python-visible RAM, clearly outperformed both strategies. This outcome demonstrates how, in comparison to conventional Pandas workflows, current algorithms like Polars can significantly increase performance and memory economy.\n",
        "\n",
        "| Finding | Most Effective |\n",
        "| :--- | :--- |\n",
        "| Fastest Execution | Polars — 3.73s (19.33× faster than Pandas) |\n",
        "| Lowest Memory Usage (Python-visible) | Polars — 0.02 MB |\n",
        "| Lowest Memory Usage (Pandas-based strategies) | Chunking — 151 MB |\n",
        "| Easiest to Implement | Pandas |\n",
        "| Best Migration Path from Pandas | Dask |\n",
        "| Best for Production Pipelines | Polars |\n",
        "\n",
        "### 6.2 Reflection\n",
        "Several results in this assignment were different from what we initially expected.\n",
        "\n",
        "Given that both Polars and Dask offer parallel processing, we expected that Dask would perform more closely to Polars. But the difference—26.09 seconds for Dask against 3.73 seconds for Polars—was far more than predicted. This made a crucial contrast clear: Polars use a Rust-based engine that enables real multitasking execution without Python overhead, whereas Dask implements parallelism at the Python level (on Pandas operations). This demonstrates that \"parallel\" does not always imply the same degree of performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "At first, we were also surprised by Polars' 0.02 MB memory figure and assumed it might be a measurement error. After further research, we discovered that Polars allocates the majority of memory outside of Python in Rust, but `tracemalloc` exclusively tracks Python memory. This transformed an odd outcome into a valuable lesson on the operation of memory profiling tools.\n",
        "\n",
        "Additionally, we came across a frequent problem with mismatched column names (e.g., using `FlightDate` instead of `fl_date`). This brought to light a crucial practical lesson: before coding, always confirm column names using the dataset directly. Errors and unnecessary debugging can be avoided with basic checks like `df.columns`.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 6.3 Scalability Discussion\n",
        "The methods examined in this assignment perform well at the 1.22 GB scale, but as data sizes grow, their shortcomings become more apparent.\n",
        "\n",
        "Memory limitations make it challenging to run Pandas without chunking on average computers at about 10 GB. On a multi-core system, Dask can manage this scale effectively without requiring significant modifications. Because Polars uses `scan_csv()`to process data lazily—that is, without loading the entire dataset into memory at once—it also operates effectively on a single machine.\n",
        "\n",
        "Single-machine processing is no longer possible at 1 TB and more. It becomes essential to use cloud platforms like AWS, Google Cloud, or Azure and distributed systems like Apache Spark. Data engineering at this scale usually includes data warehouses like BigQuery or Snowflake in addition to distributed storage and computing technologies.\n",
        "\n",
        "In general, real-world data engineering practice is reflected in the progression from Pandas to Dask and Polars, and finally to Spark and cloud systems. This assignment illustrates the point at which more advanced, scalable systems are required when traditional tools begin to fail.\n",
